rban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Creke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from North or South Creake in Norfolk, named from Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘cliff, rock’.","English: from Middle English <i>creke</i> ‘basket’ (Old French <i>creche</i>), hence a metonymic occupational name for a basket maker.","Americanized form of German   Krieg   or <b>Krück</b> (see   Kruck  ), or German and Jewish   Krick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Krieg","meanings":["Swiss German, German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for an argumentative person, from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>kriec</i>, German <i>Krieg</i> ‘strife, conflict, squabble’ (Yiddish <i>krig</i>). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine).","German: variant of the plural form of   Krug  ."]},{"name":"Crick","meanings":["English: habitational name from Crick in Northamptonshire, from Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘rock, cliff’.","English: occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived by an inlet, from a Middle English borrowing of Old Norse <i>kriki</i>.","Possibly also an Americanized form of any of the German and Dutch surnames mentioned at   Creek   3."]},{"name":"Creeks","meanings":["English (Durham): variant of   Creek  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Bartholomew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of New Testament origin, the name of an apostle mentioned in all the synoptic gospels (Matthew, Mark, and Luke) and in the Acts of the Apostles. It is an Aramaic formation meaning ‘son of Talmai’, and has been assumed by many scholars to be a byname of the apostle   Nathaniel .  <i>Talmai</i> is a Hebrew name, said to mean ‘abounding in furrows’ (Numbers 13:22)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Bartholomew de Creke was born about 1109, in Docking, Norfolk, England as the son of Bartholemew de Crec I. He married Alice de Cokefeld. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1189, in North Creake, Norfolk, England, at the age of 81."},"et":{"about 1109–1189":"umbes 1109–1189","1109–1189":"1109–1189","1132–Female":"1132–Surnud","1163–1233":"1163–1233","1109–1161":"1109–1161","about 1109":"umbes 1109","1189":"1189","1233":"1233","1132":"1132","1163":"1163","1161":"1161","1109":"1109","North Creake, Norfolk, England":"North Creake, Norfolk, England","Docking, Norfolk, England":"Docking, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1109–1189":"noin 1109–1189","1109–1189":"1109–1189","1132–Female":"1132–Kuollut","1163–1233":"1163–1233","1109–1161":"1109–1161","about 1109":"noin 1109","1189":"1189","1233":"1233","1132":"1132","1163":"1163","1161":"1161","1109":"1109","North Creake, Norfolk, England":"North Creake, Norfolk, England","Docking, Norfolk, England":"Docking, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1109–1189":"environ 1109–1189","1109–1189":"1109–1189","1132–Female":"1132–Décédée","1163–1233":"1163–1233","1109–1161":"1109–1161","about 1109":"environ 1109","1189":"1189","1233":"1233","1132":"1132","1163":"1163","1161":"1161","1109":"1109","North Creake, Norfolk, England":"North Creake, Norfolk, Angleterre","Docking, Norfolk, England":"Docking, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Bartholomew de Creke est né environ 1109, à Docking, Norfolk, Angleterre, fils de Bartholemew de Crec I. Il a épousé Alice de Cokefeld. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1189, à North Creak